John,

That sounds like a reasonable hypothesis to me.  Proper spelling is 
engrained in most people today, but I believe that in Elizabethan times 
the concept of a &quot;correct&quot; spelling was either non-existent or much 
weaker.  I would argue that if it is clear what word you are intending 
to represent, a slightly different spelling from an arbitrary &quot;standard&quot; 
should cause no difficulty in reading.

I think it is fair to say that most languages are not spread around the 
globe as widely as English is so alternate pronunciations in English may 
be more likely to occur.  Another point is that English seems peculiarly 
resistant to modification of standardized spelling over time when 
pronunciation has changed as compared to other languages such as German 
or Spanish.  Perhaps that is due to the independent nature of the 
English Speaking Peoples.

I have not gone back and checked the group messages from the past, but I 
remember long detailed discussions about how necessary standardizing QS 
spelling was.  The people pushing this idea seem much more focused on 
this than seems necessary to me, and they seemed very adamant about it.  
I see it as a slippery slope. Okay, now that we have straightened out 
English spelling and made it sensible again, let&#39;s start back down the 
same path that got us into this mess to begin with.

Regards,


Paige Gabhart

P.S.  The state of English spelling brings about other unanticipated 
results.  Recently, I have noticed people spelling the names of their 
children in ways that do not follow normal English spelling precepts.  
These parents appear to believe that letters may be freely put into 
words and then ignored in the pronunciation of the resulting name.  I 
guess the letter is stuck in to provide &quot;uniqueness.&quot;  Example:  
&quot;Elijiah,&quot; but pronounced according to the parent as &quot;Elijah;&quot; or 
&quot;Tanikia&quot; pronounced &quot;Tanika.&quot;  I suspect if you asked them what the 
extra, unpronounced &quot;i&quot; was for, they would look at you blankly.  This 
may go back to the number of exceptions that actual English spelling 
presents when compared to the standard spelling rules.  I think many 
people do not understand the concept that each letter should represent a 
sound present in the word.

The idea of the existence of &quot;silent&quot; letters brings this out.  A couple 
of years ago I learned of an elementary teacher who was telling her 
young students that the &quot;h&quot; in words such as &quot;which&quot; and &quot;why&quot; was a 
silent letter.  Presumably, for her it was, but I suspect she had no 
idea that many people still pronounce it and consider it important.  No 
wonder it is a dying sound with that lack of knowledge on the part of 
the people teaching our children.


